messages.message: does anybody know about the Inspector app? I’m hunting down (and deleting) ghost apps that live in the code but aren’t being surfaced in any way, and this appears to be one of them
it seems to be a tool to examine what is inside a flow binary? I honestly have no idea who we should ask about this. It is fairly broken right now though

@cross talk - a podcast about crosswords - listen on apple podcasts or spotify (hey, just now noticed your Slack handle, darth caul... cool)
Do you know about CD-96 (https://instabase.atlassian.net/browse/CD-96) to categorize and clean up apps? tldr; see this App lifecycle doc (https://docs.google.com/document/d/1eG2jpvYIV_9NHkzsGPk8pgcGobC2_ScPLQAC7Jb1Zac/edit#heading=h.ah80v4z5fswu) that doesn't even mention Inspector

messages.message: @Barrie yep, this doc is what sent me down the rabbit hole trying to find all the ghost apps in the first place!
Not entirely sure about this, but I believe at one point Capital One wanted to tag and sign flow binaries.
Jess Lin, the engineer who implemented features for that desire, created two apps
Flow Inspector allowed one to view the tags and signatures on a binary
Flow Lifecycle allowed one to add tags and signatures to a binary
I don't believe either app ever got used in production: the team at Capital one that wanted the feature is no longer using Instabase
